  "Short-term goals are those you plan to achieve within 3 years, such as building an emergency fund, saving for a vacation, or paying off a credit card balance.": "",
  "Net worth is calculated as:": "",
  "Income minus expenses": "",
  "Assets minus liabilities": "",
  "Income times years worked": "",
  "Savings times interest rate": "",
  "Net worth equals total assets (savings, investments, property, retirement accounts) minus total liabilities (mortgages, student loans, credit card debt, car loans). It is the primary measure of overall financial health.": "",
  "Long-term goals (10+ years) typically include:": "",
  "Building an emergency fund": "",
  "Paying this month's rent": "",
  "Retirement savings and children's college funds": "",
  "Saving for a vacation next summer": "",
  "Long-term goals with horizons of 10 or more years include retirement savings, children's education funds, and paying off a mortgage. These goals benefit most from compound growth over extended time periods.": "",
  "The Rule of 72 estimates that money doubles at 7% return in approximately:": "",
  "20 years": "",
  "15 years": "",
  "7 years": "",
  "About 10.3 years": "",
  "The Rule of 72 divides 72 by the annual return rate: 72 / 7 = approximately 10.3 years to double. This quick mental math tool helps estimate how long investments take to grow.": "",
  "If you have $50,000 in assets and $30,000 in liabilities, your net worth is:": "",
  "$30,000": "",
  "$50,000": "",
  "$20,000": "",
  "$80,000": "",
  "$50,000 in assets minus $30,000 in liabilities equals $20,000 net worth. This positive net worth means your assets exceed your debts, which is the goal of financial planning.": "",
  "A 25-year-old's financial priorities should typically be, in order:": "",
  "100% spending on current lifestyle": "",
  "Only focus on debt elimination": "",
  "Only focus on retirement savings": "",
  "Build emergency fund, pay off high-interest debt, start retirement saving, invest for growth": "",
  "The recommended priority order builds a secure foundation first: emergency fund (prevents new debt), high-interest debt payoff (stops interest drain), then retirement saving (maximizes compound growth), and broader investing.": "",
  "Inflation of 3% means $100,000 in 20 years has the purchasing power of approximately:": "",
  "$40,000": "",
  "About $55,400": "",
  "$100,000": "",
  "$100,000 times (0.97)^20 = $100,000 times 0.5537 = approximately $55,368. Inflation erodes purchasing power over time, making it critical to invest at rates that outpace inflation.": "",
