  "$1,000,000": "",
  "$400,000": "",
  "$600,000": "",
  "$2,000,000": "",
  "The 4% rule suggests you can safely withdraw 4% of your portfolio annually in retirement. Working backward: $40,000 / 0.04 = $1,000,000 needed (or equivalently, 25 times annual expenses).": "",
  "What is the financial planning lifecycle?": "",
  "The process of borrowing money and repaying it": "",
  "The progression from the accumulation phase (earning and saving during working years) to the distribution phase (spending savings in retirement)": "",
  "The cycle of investing only in stocks and bonds": "",
  "A single financial plan that never changes throughout your life": "",
  "The financial lifecycle has two main phases: accumulation (working years where you earn, save, and grow wealth) and distribution (retirement years where you draw down savings). Planning must account for the transition between these phases.": "",
  "What is financial independence?": "",
  "Having a high-paying job, particularly when annual considerations are weighed against competing pressures": "",
  "Never needing any money at all, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "Being completely debt-free without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "Having enough passive income or savings that working for money is optional, often calculated as 25 times annual expenses": "",
  "Financial independence (FI) means your investment income and savings can cover all expenses indefinitely without employment income. The FI number is typically 25 times annual expenses, allowing a safe 4% annual withdrawal rate.": "",
  "What is estate planning?": "",
  "Only writing a will, since standard models of estate behavior predict this outcome under normal conditions": "",
  "Planning to buy real estate property, since standard models of estate behavior predict this outcome under normal conditions": "",
  "Something only wealthy people need, since standard models of estate behavior predict this outcome under normal conditions": "",
  "Creating legal documents (will, power of attorney, healthcare directive, beneficiary designations) to manage your assets and wishes after death or incapacity": "",
  "Estate planning involves creating legal documents to ensure your assets are distributed according to your wishes and your affairs are managed if you become incapacitated. It includes wills, trusts, powers of attorney, healthcare directives, and beneficiary designations.": "",
  "What is the 4% rule in retirement planning?": "",
  "4% of your income should go to an emergency fund because conventional analysis of retirement suggests this would be the expected result": "",
  "A guideline suggesting you can withdraw 4% of your retirement portfolio in the first year, adjusting for inflation thereafter, with a high probability of the money lasting 30 years": "",
  "Investments should earn at least 4% annually based on the conventional understanding of how retirement processes interact in practice": "",
  "You should save 4% of income for retirement, as the dynamics involved tend to push conditions in this direction over time": "",
  "The 4% rule, based on the Trinity Study, suggests withdrawing 4% of your portfolio in year one of retirement and adjusting for inflation each subsequent year. Historically, this approach has sustained portfolios for 30+ years.": "",
  "What is a medium-term financial goal?": "",
  "A goal with a 0-1 year timeline": "",
  "A goal with a 20+ year timeline": "",
  "A goal that costs a medium amount of money": "",
  "A goal with a 3-10 year timeline, such as saving for a home down payment or graduate school": "",
  "Medium-term goals fall between short-term (0-3 years) and long-term (10+ years). Common examples include saving for a home down payment, funding graduate school, or buying a car. These may use a mix of savings and conservative investments.": "",
  "What does 'time value of money' mean in financial planning?": "",
  "Time is worth more than money": "",
  "You should spend money now because it will be worth less later": "",
  "A dollar today is worth more than a dollar in the future because today's dollar can be invested to earn returns": "",
  "The time it takes to earn a certain amount of money": "",
  "The time value of money (TVM) is the foundational concept that money available now is worth more than the same amount in the future due to its earning potential. $1,000 today invested at 7% becomes $1,967 in 10 years.": "",
  "What is the accumulation phase?": "",
  "The first year of a new investment": "",
  "The working years during which you earn income, save, invest, and build wealth for future goals": "",
  "The period when you pay off all debts": "",
  "The period when you withdraw money from retirement accounts": "",
  "The accumulation phase spans your working years when you actively earn income and build wealth through saving and investing. The goal is to grow assets sufficiently to fund retirement and other long-term goals.": "",
  "What is the distribution phase?": "",
  "The retirement years when you draw down accumulated savings and investments to fund living expenses": "",
  "The period when you make the most money": "",
  "The phase when a company distributes dividends": "",
  "The period when you distribute money to charity only": "",
  "The distribution phase begins at retirement when the focus shifts from building wealth to strategically drawing it down. Careful withdrawal planning ensures savings last throughout retirement.": "",
  "What is a power of attorney?": "",
  "The right to practice law, as most introductory frameworks would predict when analyzing attorney dynamics": "",
  "A type of life insurance policy in most scenarios involving attorney factors": "",
  "A legal document that gives someone authority to make financial or medical decisions on your behalf if you become incapacitated": "",
  "A government-issued ID, since standard models of attorney behavior predict this outcome under normal conditions": "",
  "A power of attorney (POA) is a legal document designating a trusted person to manage your financial or healthcare affairs if you are unable to do so. Financial POA covers money matters; healthcare POA covers medical decisions.": "",
  "What does 'asset allocation' mean in long-term planning?": "",
  "The strategic distribution of investments across different asset classes (stocks, bonds, cash) based on goals, risk tolerance, and time horizon": "",
  "Selling all investments and holding only cash": "",
  "Dividing your paycheck among different bank accounts": "",
  "Allocating all money to the highest-returning investment": "",
  "Asset allocation divides your investment portfolio among different asset classes -- stocks, bonds, and cash -- based on your goals, how much risk you can tolerate, and when you need the money. Younger investors typically hold more stocks; older investors shift toward bonds.": "",
  "A 30-year-old couple has $25,000 in savings, $15,000 in retirement accounts, a car worth $12,000, and a home worth $280,000. Their debts include: $210,000 mortgage, $8,000 car loan, and $22,000 student loans. What is their net worth?": "",
  "$240,000": "",
  "$92,000": "",
  "$332,000": "",
  "-$8,000": "",
  "Assets: $25,000 + $15,000 + $12,000 + $280,000 = $332,000. Liabilities: $210,000 + $8,000 + $22,000 = $240,000. Net worth: $332,000 - $240,000 = $92,000. This positive net worth shows they are building wealth despite significant debts.": "",
  "Lisa starts saving $300/month for retirement at age 25. Her colleague Mark starts saving $600/month at age 40. Both earn 7% average annual returns and retire at 65. Who has more at retirement, and approximately how much more?": "",
  "Lisa has about $438,000 more despite saving less per month, because she had 15 extra years of compounding": "",
  "Mark has more because he saves double the monthly amount": "",
  "Mark has about $200,000 more": "",
  "They end up with approximately the same amount": "",
  "Lisa: $300/month for 40 years at 7% = approximately $791,000. Total contributed: $144,000. Mark: $600/month for 25 years at 7% = approximately $456,000. Total contributed: $180,000. Lisa has about $335,000 more despite contributing $36,000 less. Time is the most powerful factor in compound growth.": "",
  "A family wants to save $120,000 for their newborn's college education in 18 years. If they invest at 7% average return, approximately how much must they save per month?": "",
  "About $278/month": "",
  "$556/month": "",
  "$500/month": "",
  "$200/month": "",
  "Without any investment return, they would need $120,000 / 216 months = $556/month. But at 7% compounded monthly, the FV annuity formula shows approximately $278/month is sufficient. Investment returns cut the required savings roughly in half over 18 years.": "",
  "A 35-year-old earns $80,000/year and wants to retire at 65 with $1,500,000. She currently has $50,000 in retirement savings. Assuming 7% annual returns, approximately how much must she save per month for the next 30 years?": "",
