  "A 28-year-old has $40,000 in student loans at 5% and wants to know: should she aggressively pay off loans or invest the extra money in an index fund averaging 10% historically? What does the math suggest?": "",
  "Always pay off all debt before investing given that prevailing loan conditions tend to reinforce this particular trajectory": "",
  "Always invest instead of paying off any debt due to the well-established relationship between loan trends and broader outcomes": "",
  "The math favors investing the extra money since the expected 10% return exceeds the 5% loan rate, yielding a 5% net gain; but also consider risk tolerance and the guaranteed 'return' of debt payoff": "",
  "The 5% interest makes the loan free money, as the dynamics involved tend to push conditions in this direction over time": "",
  "Mathematically, if investments average 10% and the loan costs 5%, investing creates a 5% net advantage. However, investment returns are not guaranteed while the loan interest is certain. The optimal strategy often involves investing (especially for employer match) while making regular loan payments, but risk-averse individuals may prefer the guaranteed savings of debt payoff.": "",
  "A comprehensive financial plan for a 40-year-old family includes: emergency fund ($24,000), college savings needing $150,000 in 12 years, retirement needing $1,200,000 in 25 years, and current retirement savings of $180,000. Assuming 7% returns, approximately how much total must they save monthly across all goals?": "",
